                                <condition><p>The stone has some minor scratches and fractures with some wear.</p></condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout><p>The stone is approximately of a rectangular shape, with face A accompanied by two lines of Latin writing, while face B contains the ogham inscription of the first ten letters of the alphabet and a <rs type="decoration">cruciform, curvilinear design and two intersecting lines terminating in spirals</rs>.</p></layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote><p>The ogham inscription is incomplete, consisting of only the first ten letters of the alphabet on a drawn-in stemline running horizontally in the middle of the slab. The stem begins about <dim type="length" unit="m">0.010</dim> from the left edge with the end lost in the fractured top right corner. Forsyth and Tedeschi comment that the two inscriptions, latin and ogham, appear to have possibly been <rs type="execution" key="carved" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/168.html">carved</rs> by the same hand. However there is not sufficient evidence to argue that the ogham inscription has not been added at a later date.The carver has managed to write the ogham in neatly parallel and equidistant individual strokes with the exception of the final stroke not reaching the stem. The care with which it was carved is consistent with it being a type of exercise. The letters of the H-group, as Forsyth and Tedeschi comment <q>'exhibit a consistent forward slope, ie their distal tips (furthest from the stem) are further forward (to the right) of their approximal tips'</q> with letters of the B-group slope on this same axis.</p>
                               <!-- <height>length of ogham stroke, if known</height>-->
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
