            <div type="commentary">
                 <list type="witDetail">
                   <item n="1">
                        <p>Forsyth and Tedeschi comment that <q>'this is the first find of non-monumental ogham from an ecclestial site'</q> (2008,130)</p>
                    </item>
                     <item n="2">
                         <p>From the Inchmarnock ogham inscriptions it is clear that <q>'Gaelic-speaking scribes were familiar with the ogham alphabet and used it in informal sometimes jocular way, for brief marginal glosses and comments'</q> (Forsyth and Tedeschi 2008,130)</p>
                     </item>
                     <item n="3">
                         <p>This slate in particular, as Forsyth and Tedeschi comment, implies<q>'that the script was being actively taught in the monastery's school'</q> (2008,131)</p>
                     </item>
                     <item n="4">
                         <p>The form of script on the Inchmarnock ogham inscriptions is <q>'simple and devoid of baroque, 'supplamentary' letters</q> common of later east Scottish oghams (Forsyth and Tedeschi 2008,131)</p>
                     </item>
                     <item n="5">
                         <p>The sloping of consonant strokes, such as found on the Inchmarnock ogham, is rarer in Ireland, in both epigraphic and manuscript ogham (Forsyth and Tedeschi 2008).</p>
                     </item>
                 </list>
            </div>
